The underlying rule: Recognition → Constraint → Generative Response within Tolerance
A jazz musician doesn’t play randomly. They read the harmonic context (what key, what chord, what the bassist just did), apply a constraint set (scales, rhythmic feel, dynamic range), and then generate novel output within that space. The constraint doesn’t kill creativity — it is the creativity engine. Remove the constraint and you get noise, not jazz.
An immune cell doesn’t fire randomly either. It reads molecular context (antigen shape, MHC presentation, cytokine signals), applies a constraint set (self/non-self tolerance, co-stimulatory requirements, clonal selection), and generates a targeted novel response. Remove the constraint and you get autoimmunity — the system attacks itself.
Same structure. Different substrate.

The deeper thing:
Both systems fail identically when the constraint layer breaks:
	•	Jazz without harmonic grounding → cacophony
	•	Immune system without tolerance → lupus
And both systems learn by updating the constraint layer, not the generative layer. The musician doesn’t learn new notes. The immune system doesn’t learn new amino acids. They learn better pattern discrimination.

What this implies:
Intelligence — real intelligence — isn’t generative power.
It’s the quality of your constraint layer.
